 to the authoritarian methods of Louis XIV and perpetuated the Sun King's political and economic legacy.This study calls into question current revisionist understanding of Louis XIV and insists that absolute government had a harsh reality at its core. Based upon extensive archival research, this remarkable book will be of interest to all students of the history of early modern France and the monarchies of Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonarchyzFrancexHistoryy17th century. 0aParlements (French courts). 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aLouis XIV.  aParlement of Paris.  aPhilippe d'Orleans.  aSun King.  aabsolute government.  anew legislation.  aparlements of France.  aprovincial tribunals.  areign.  astrict political discipline.1 aHurt, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137487zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137487zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137487/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA